  "text": "Rust macro expansion and HIR lowering follows a well-defined pipeline in the rust-lang/rust compiler. The process occurs in several key stages:\n\n## 1. Macro Expansion Entry Point\n\nThe compilation pipeline starts in `compiler/rustc_interface/src/passes.rs` at line 219, where `MacroExpander::expand_crate()` is called to expand all macros in the crate. This is orchestrated by the `macro_expand_crate` function which creates an `ExtCtxt` (expansion context) and invokes the macro expander.\n\n## 2. Macro Invocation Collection and Expansion\n\nThe main expansion logic is in `compiler/rustc_expand/src/expand.rs`. The `MacroExpander` struct (defined at line 458) has several key methods:\n\n- `expand_crate()` (line 468): Entry point that walks the entire crate AST\n- `fully_expand_fragment()` (line 489): Recursively expands all macro invocations in an AST fragment, handling both declarative and procedural macros\n- `collect_invocations()` (line 642): Traverses the AST to find all macro invocations and replaces them with placeholders using the `InvocationCollector` visitor\n- `expand_invoc()` (line 716): Expands individual macro invocations by dispatching to the appropriate macro implementation\n\nDuring collection, the `InvocationCollector` visitor identifies three types of macros: Bang macros (like `println!()`), Attribute macros, and Derive macros. These are stored as `Invocation` structures (defined at line 380+) which contain the macro invocation kind and metadata.\n\n## 3. Token Stream Transformation for Declarative Macros\n\nFor `macro_rules!` (declarative) macros, the expansion process involves:\n\n- **Pattern Matching**: `compiler/rustc_expand/src/mbe/macro_parser.rs` implements an NFA-based parser (`TtParser` struct) that matches the input token stream against macro rules. The parser handles Kleene operators and nested sequences, as documented in the extensive module-level comments starting at line 1.\n\n- **Token Transcription**: `compiler/rustc_expand/src/mbe/transcribe.rs` contains the `transcribe()` function (line 163) which transforms matched tokens into output tokens. The `TranscrCtx` struct (line 29) manages transcription state including:\n  - `interp`: Map from metavariables to matched tokens\n  - `stack`: Expansion stack for nested constructs\n  - `result`: Accumulated token stream output\n\nThe transcription process walks through the macro RHS (right-hand side), substituting matched metavariables and handling repetitions according to Kleene operators.\n\n## 4. Procedural Macro Execution\n\nProcedural macros (function-like, attribute, and derive macros) are handled differently:\n\n- `compiler/rustc_expand/src/proc_macro.rs` (line 40-100) defines `BangProcMacro` and `AttrProcMacro` traits that implement the `expand()` method. These set up the proc macro execution environment and communicate with the proc macro via a message-passing bridge.\n\n- `compiler/rustc_expand/src/proc_macro_server.rs` (line 436) defines the `Rustc` struct which implements the server side of the proc macro bridge, translating between the compiler's `TokenStream` and the proc macro's token representation.\n\nThe expansion happens in-process via the bridge mechanism, which executes the proc macro code and collects its output.\n\n## 5. AST Parsing from Token Stream\n\nOnce macros are expanded (whether declarative or procedural), the resulting token stream is parsed back into AST fragments. In `compiler/rustc_expand/src/expand.rs` at line 747, the `parse_ast_fragment()` function is called to convert the token stream output into AST nodes. The function is defined at line 1066 and takes the expanded token stream and fragment kind to produce the appropriate AST node type.\n\nThe `AstFragment` enum (defined in the `ast_fragments!` macro at line 49 of expand.rs) represents the different types of AST fragments that can be produced: expressions, items, statements, types, patterns, etc.\n\n## 6. HIR Lowering from Expanded AST\n\nAfter all macros are expanded, the complete AST is lowered to HIR (High-level Intermediate Representation):\n\n- The entry point is `lower_to_hir()` in `compiler/rustc_ast_lowering/src/lib.rs` (line 485), registered as a query provider at `compiler/rustc_interface/src/passes.rs` line 888.\n\n- `LoweringContext` (line 91 in lib.rs) is the main structure managing the lowering process, maintaining:\n  - The `arena` for allocating HIR nodes\n  - `resolver`: Symbol resolution information\n  - `bodies`: Collected function bodies\n  - Various context state (loop scopes, async contexts, etc.)\n\n- Item lowering is handled in `compiler/rustc_ast_lowering/src/item.rs` where `lower_item()` (line 136) converts AST items to HIR items. Similar functions exist for expressions, patterns, types, etc. in their respective modules (expr.rs, pat.rs, path.rs, etc.).\n\n## Complete Flow Summary\n\nThe macro expansion to HIR lowering chain is:\n\n1. `macro_expand_crate` (in passes.rs) calls\n2. `MacroExpander::expand_crate()` which calls\n3. `fully_expand_fragment()` which:\n   - Calls `collect_invocations()` to find all macro invocations\n   - Calls `expand_invoc()` on each invocation, which dispatches to:\n     - For declarative macros: `TtParser::parse_tt()` + `transcribe()`\n     - For procedural macros: `BangProcMacro::expand()` / `AttrProcMacro::expand()`\n   - Calls `parse_ast_fragment()` to convert token streams to AST\n4. The fully expanded AST is then passed to\n5. `lower_to_hir()` which uses `LoweringContext` to convert AST to HIR\n\nThis pipeline maintains span information throughout to enable error reporting and source mapping, uses hygiene information to ensure macro-generated identifiers are properly scoped, and handles both eager (macro_rules with special evaluation semantics) and lazy (most macros) expansion modes."
